1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Today is Tuesday, September 13, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier, I'm the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:30,000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop, we are in St. Augustine Florida at the Bayfront Hilton Hotel.

4
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:39,000
To do a set of interviews related to civil rights history in St. Augustine with various folks and were delighted and very privileged to sit down Mr. Purcell Maurice Conway.

5
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Thank you very much for taking time and being so flexible today. It's been a little bit unusual as we've bounced out our day, but thank you for sitting down.

6
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Any comments, John, for the take on Noxby?

7
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:02,000
We are not recording to Ex-D and I think with to the Ex-D cars and I think with that we can begin.

8
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:25,000
I would like to thank you for taking the time to document this.

9
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:42,000
I did forget one thing on the tape and I need to say I beg your pardon. This is a civil rights history project interview for joint sponsors, the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress for giving me.

10
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:58,000
I started by just my history of growing up in St. Augustine, particularly Lincolnville, it's a black, self-sufficient community.

11
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:17,000
I recall early on just the feel of Lincolnville, it was a heavenly place to grow up. All the adults knew you. I knew most of the kids in Lincolnville.

12
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:36,000
I was raised after the age of five by my great-great-grandmother, Mr. Jorobinson. She was a Seminole Indian and Spanish mixed.

13
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:50,000
She raised me with the understanding that I would acknowledge the adults, be respectful, don't steal, don't lie. That's how I was raised.

14
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:09,000
My mother and father and my three brothers moved out to a brand new development in West Augustine and that's where they reside on Scotts Street.

15
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:29,000
The rotting subdivision, newly developed. I recall as a child getting up in the morning, I could run from sun up to sun down throughout Lincolnville with no problems.

16
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:47,000
I was no concern about the children because all the adults in Lincolnville were watched out for the children. I spent most of my time, particularly at the little links, which is also housing the Galimore Center today.

17
00:03:47,000 --> 00:04:01,000
It was the only black park in St. Augustine. It's the only place blacks could go for recreation. There was a lot of recreation when I was growing up.

18
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:19,000
You had football teams organized throughout the city. You had softball games with the adults at night. We had an instructor there, Mr. Eddie Lee Vickers, who ran the facility.

19
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:35,000
I was amazed that you could go in. You had ping pong, you had pool tables. You had all sorts of activities. Even the man was training some of the kids to play tennis, archery. I was just amazed you could do all this for nothing.

20
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:48,000
I would spend most of my time as a youth. There was a little links. The biggest problem growing up as a child is money. Money was very scarce.

21
00:04:48,000 --> 00:05:00,000
I called off and thinking, well, I got to find a way to put a little change in my pockets for my candy and ice cream because my great grandmother just didn't have it all the time.

22
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:11,000
I never get to go to Washington Street one day. I saw these white people boys on their bicycles riding away from the St. Augustine record. I'm thinking, wow.

23
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:25,000
I was not supposed to go in that part of town. That was a white area. It was only a block across from Washington Street. That was a white area. You didn't go there unless you were accompanied by an adult.

24
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:41,000
I would stay in there daily and watch these white people boys riding away from the St. Augustine record. I worked up the courage one day. I was 10 years old to venture over there and ask for a job.

25
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:55,000
I went in and I called speaking to this white gentleman and I'd say, well, look. I like to be a paper boy. Can I be a paper boy? He looked down and he said, well, how old are you? I told him I was 10.

26
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:10,000
He said, well, okay. I'll give you a try. Come back tomorrow. I left there happy as a log. I went in and I told my great grandma, I said, mama, I got a job as a paper boy.

27
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:24,000
She was happy. She said, you're dead. I told you not to go over there. Since you went there, okay, you got a job. I want you to sell, you cannot go out of Lincolnville. They're trying to sell papers.

28
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:36,000
She lined up my shirt. I lined up my bicycle. I went in the next day and it gave me a few papers. I went throughout Lincolnville trying to sell them.

29
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:59,000
After a period of about two weeks, it didn't work out too well. I'm not on a hot sun. Three, four, five hours a day. I made 10 cents. It wasn't too good. I started thinking, well, maybe I'm not too good at this. I can't make any money. It's not worth staying around making 10 cents. Pretty much most of the day.

30
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:19,000
This one particular day, I'm thinking, wow, how can I make more money? I'm sorry. You got that big Castillo de San Marcos there in the downtown area, a white area. I know I'm not supposed to go over there, but I need you to give it a shot.

31
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:38,000
I came over here one day, at the Castillo de San Marcos. I stood in front of the Castillo de San Marcos. Within about an hour, I sold every paper I had. I had to go back to the St. Augustine record and get more papers. I came back in an hour. I sold all of those. I went back a third time and got papers.

32
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:56,000
I sold all of those. People would come out of the Castillo de San Marcos and look at me and take pictures. I was a cute kid. I was happy. That first day I worked at the Castillo de San Marcos. I had never made a dollar bill. I had about four or five in my pocket. I couldn't believe it.

33
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:10,000
This went on for a few weeks. I'd go in and pick up my papers and you'd have a line of white paper boys. I would always be allowed to go right up to the front window and get my papers.

34
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:31,000
I would say, wow, I guess that treat me great. The only black kid here. I put me up the front line. I get my papers. I didn't see the sign colored. I was only a paper boy at the time. I'd not even wear a race or anything else.

35
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:47,000
I came in one day and what are the white men this? You sell more papers in three days in this whole group in a week. You said, what are you doing? I just squat and I asked the people to buy the papers.

36
00:08:47,000 --> 00:09:08,000
Before that, I actually see some of the white paper boys on their bikes trying to follow me. I circle around, circle around and lose them. This one particular. I don't get they do follow me. I had two white paper boys to follow me up to the Castillo de San Marcos. They took positions to my left and right.

37
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I always saw people who came out of the Castillo de San Marcos. They would come out and look. They would look at me and look at the two white kids and they started buying paper from them. Either one of the white guys.

38
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Being a tenure rep from what is going on, I'm trying to figure out, I'm looking at my shirt as my shirt dirty. I'm looking at my pants and my pants dirty. I couldn't figure out what was going on but they would come out of the Castillo de San Marcos. They'd take a look and they'd buy from me either one of the white kids.

39
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:59,000
They'd be in the hands of me. One guy would blow out my hair and blow out my pants. I was pretty sharp looking kid. I never get I sat on the curb there across from the Castillo de San Marcos. I forgot what was going on. I can't understand what was going on.

40
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:23,000
It happened for a few days until the point I said, look, I see people not going to buy papers from me. I don't know why. I had to find another location. I did find another location. It wasn't as good as the Castillo de San Marcos. I can see the life of a paper boy is only a year or two. I had to look for another work.

41
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:36,000
I worked throughout St. Augustine in many locations. The only thing you get pretty much at that time was washing dishes, washing pots or cleaning up floors.

42
00:10:36,000 --> 00:11:05,000
I managed to eat out a little living out of it. I kept money in my pocket. I'm in high school now. I'm really disenchanted with the high school. I would challenge my teachers about the books being four or five years old written in. I would always be told, well, just stop making a fuss.

43
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Fortunately for me, my uncle, Edward Norton, who moved in New York with his family, left for a small library of books. At that time, I loved to read. I never get his medical books.

44
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:40,000
I had a little more advanced education than most of the kids in my high school. I would even challenge some of the teachers with some of the things they would say about the history behind some of the books that my uncle left.

45
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:49,000
I was considered somewhat of trouble making a rebel rouser. I always thought I was a smart student.

46
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:06,000
But there was no change. Then I started seeing the way my mother particularly would be treated when she'd come up town, a downtown by clothing, and by goods.

47
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:23,000
It was always Julia, this. Julia, that. She would respond, miss, so-and-so, and miss that. It started annoying me. Why isn't she being called miss? Why does she always have to call someone miss, a mister?

48
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:42,000
I started to get annoyed with that. I didn't say anything to hurt, but I was annoyed. They started a program in my high school called the DCT where you would get credits for working outside of school.

49
00:12:42,000 --> 00:13:00,000
I thought it was a joke. I thought the program was a joke. Are they going to give you credits for working? That's all I've been doing since I was 10. So that's why I joined this program, which I did. And teacher approaches me when they answer, well, well, we have to find you a job. I said, I have a job.

50
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Oh, all right. Well, get your employer to fill up this form so that you can get credit for it. And I was working out at a land of stage island with my father at a grocery store there. And I took the form to the owner.

51
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:27,000
That's what would you mind filling this out so I could get credit in high school for working here. You said, no, you don't want to get involved.

52
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:41,000
That's why not I've been working for you for the last couple of years. Well, no, I'm not going to sign it. Now, at the time, I'm in about the eighth and ninth grade. And I was doing this guy's accounting.

53
00:13:41,000 --> 00:14:10,000
He showed me how to go into his back and order whatever goods he needed. And I was doing that plus stocking groceries. And he was only paying me $40 for working pretty much a 50 day week. I mean, 50 out a week. And he refused to sign. I said, I'll tell you what, I quit. I'll get another job. And he said, oh, wait a minute. Wait a minute. No. And I was a good worker.

54
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:24,000
And I was a good worker. It's one thing. Any job I worked, I did it well. And I knew that. And he said, wait a minute. Wait a minute. Let me think this over. That's well, there's nothing to think over. I'm just asking you to fill the form. It's nothing out of your pocket.

55
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:38,000
So he came in a proper form. And I was started getting credits upon credits upon credit. I always worked. I had to work. I was staying with my great grandmother.

56
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:54,000
I didn't know poverty, but I know we didn't have much. And I tried to help out as much as I could. But I was still upset about the treatment, not only myself, my parents, my father also was working the same grocery. He wasn't making that much.

57
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:09,000
My mother, the most she could find was tourists work or some menial job. So I always growing up wanting to do something about that. I didn't know what to do. I had to do it.

58
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:24,000
So I would go to, I started going to Florida Memorial College. Like I said, it was only pool in town for blacks. A couple of my friends at high school, drowned in a sinkhole behind R.J. Murray High School.

59
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:48,000
I used to jump off the pier with a little bridge coming from West Augustine into Lincolnville. It's a little crossover. I record jumping off that pier with four or five of my friends. One dead drown in there. But there was no place for kids to swim. Black kids in particular.

60
00:15:48,000 --> 00:16:12,000
So at least the college memorial opened up their pool in the summer to a lot of the black kids. Now that's when I got involved with listening to some of the young male college students talking about demonstrating, talking about civil rights and talking about doing something about it. It intrigued me.

61
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:40,000
I was born in 1948. I actually started getting involved when I was about 14 or 15. Like I said, it intrigued me. I asked, okay. What I do recall is the training that they gave some of the kids.

62
00:16:40,000 --> 00:17:09,000
It's a came there. And one was, yes. You know, they embraced nonviolence as a tactic. So did I. But I think the ear at the time. And my ear at the time was leaning more toward some of the more, I wouldn't say radical. But the more direct speakers like Stokely Carmichael and Malcolm X.

63
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:30,000
I had heard of this, Dr. (Martin Luther) King. I found him to be very informative and passionate. But the understanding derived from the college kids nonviolent, nonviolent demonstration is the way to go.

64
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:47,000
So that's what we decided. And I decided with them to embrace. Now when the demonstration started here, yes, I remember the kids going up to sit at the counters and what have you. So I told my mother, I'm going to start demonstrating.

65
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:58,000
She said, well, I don't think it's a good thing. I said, well, mom, we got to do something. I recalled at the time that.

66
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:20,000
So struggle to get the adults more involved in the demonstrations. I felt that they were like in a trance. I just hocked me to go into the white neighborhood and see the way a lot of the blacks were being treated. That's why somebody's doing something. I say something.

67
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:31,000
So I just say myself, maybe they had a trance or something. Maybe it's so used to this particular way of being treated. It's at the point it doesn't bother them.

68
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And I used to try to talk to my mother about it. But again, you just let it go. Just let it go.

69
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:38,000
Of course, it's so much more to lose.

70
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:51,000
I don't think it was much to lose. I mean, there was there wasn't anything here. I mean, the way blacks survived in Lincolnville at the time. It wasn't for the black businesses along Washington Street.

71
00:18:51,000 --> 00:19:04,000
Most of the blacks said, a menial jobs weren't paying anything. It was more slave labor than labor. I mean, just to think about how my family eat a living, amazes me to this day.

72
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:12,000
And I guess the only thing was available was tourists, court work or taking care of some white families kid.

73
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:20,000
That was pretty much most of what blacks, particularly non professionals had to the deal with.

74
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:30,000
Now, my mother was working for this white lady out on Anastasia Island now. And I'm still trying to eat a living myself and doing little things.

75
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:41,000
I was also cutting grass. My great grandmother helped me to get a lawnmower. And I cut grass on the side.

76
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:56,000
So this, my mother asked me, my white friend, I think she was cleaning her house and keeping her kids at the time, needs her grass.

77
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:03,000
And if I drop you up at a cutter grass, you think you could do it. I said, yeah, all right, it was a hot day, extremely hot day.

78
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:13,000
I said, okay, mom, that's your friend. I said, I normally charge $15 to cut an average yard. But since it's your friend, I'll charge a 10.

79
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:22,000
So my mother drove me out with my lawnmower, dropped me at this lady's house, introduced me. And I convinced her cutting her yard.

80
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:31,000
It's very hot. So the lady comes to her drive when she calls me, Purcell, would you like a cool drink and a sandwich?

81
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:40,000
Now, say, yes, thank you, ma'am. I'm a polite of her. And when it was repaired, she came to a garage entrance again.

82
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:48,000
And so I, Purcell, you come in there, it, everything's made. So I came to the entrance of a garage and I'm looking at this wall.

83
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:53,000
Where, where, where's the sandwich in the, the sandwich ring? And she said over there.

84
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:02,000
So when I walked up, she had sit it down next to her dog, dog's tray, dog food on this side, my sandwich and water on the other side.

85
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:09,000
So I looked at this woman, I said, hmm, boy, okay, what this mentality, what is with these four?

86
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:17,000
So I said, look, miss, can I use your phone? And she said, well, what's the matter? I said, look, please, may I use your phone?

87
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:27,000
She said, okay, so she allowed me to come in a house and I called my mother and I explained to my mother what had just happened.

88
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:34,000
And I could hear the frustration in her voice. She said, could you please put her on the line?

89
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:42,000
So I did this, my mother wants to talk to you. She said, you know something, miss, so and so on. So I thought you was my friend.

90
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:47,000
I cannot believe that you would treat my child this way.

91
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:58,000
I can't believe you would treat any child this way. She said, look, I tell you what, I'll be over there picking him up immediately.

92
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:05,000
Which I'm very saddened what you just did. So the woman tried to apologize. She said, no, don't worry.

93
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:18,000
So she did. She gave me, she picked me up and we got back to our home and she said, she said, now I can see what you've been trying to explain to me.

94
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:25,000
Just the way people treat you. I can see now. And that's when she started getting involved.

95
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:35,000
Excuse me, we're back on it for short break. Let me just introduce quickly. Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling is with us for the interview as well.

96
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:42,000
And we may be rejoined by Mr. Conway's wife June as well as the afternoon progresses, please.

97
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:52,000
Okay, so I hyperticipated a number of marches with my mother insisted that I promise not to get arrested.

98
00:22:52,000 --> 00:23:01,000
Because there would be no one to, I was living still with my great-great-grandmother. And I tried to tend her and need just best I could.

99
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:07,000
So she wanted to make sure that there was always someone there with her and she asked me, please, just don't get arrested.

100
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:18,000
I don't mind you demonstrating. I said, okay, mom, I won't get arrested. So I made sure on all the marches that I stayed near the rear.

101
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:28,000
And sometimes that didn't work because too often I was chased by the police. They could never catch me. But no, I never got arrested.

102
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:38,000
And good thing. Because one particular night my mother, my father, and my three brothers were all arrested.

103
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:44,000
So I was only one out of jail. It's a good thing. I guess I was there with my great-great-grandmother.

104
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:54,000
But my parents were very active. My mother was very passionate. And my father was very supportive. And my brothers too, they were out there.

105
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:06,000
I think at one point in St. Augustine amongst black households it was a badge of honor to be arrested for the movement. And that was that passion.

106
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:16,000
And I think when the adults saw what was happening with the young, with their children and the teams out there they got motivated and totally committed.

107
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:20,000
You knew your classmate of Samuel White?

108
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:29,000
He was one year below me, yes. His brother James White was, you know, in the same home-room class.

109
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:37,000
How did young people your age kind of move through that period of time when peers were incarcerated as they were?

110
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:52,000
Or what do you, well, you know, my own personal feeling is that, you know, we as young adults saw what the system of segregation was.

111
00:24:52,000 --> 00:25:01,000
Our parents had lived under it. We were growing up in it. We decided to the death. We're not going to live this way. Sorry.

112
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:14,000
I mean, we're going to push it as far as fear. I think fear had nothing to do with it. I think when you live under oppression for so long, particularly seeing your parents live through it.

113
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:23,000
And now you're coming up through it. My thing was I, at 15, I'm going to do this for my future and my children's future.

114
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:34,000
Now, it means getting out there to the death. I'm committed. And I think that was the attitude of a lot of the young folk in high school with me.

115
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:51,000
And people talk about fear. You know, like I say, when you get fed up to the point of being mistreated that fear no longer exists for you is just doing something the anger is just doing something to break free of these chains and this oppression.

116
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:55,000
And that's what it was. Sacrification.

117
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:05,000
What memories come sharpest to your mind when you think about that long period of extended demonstration of protest?

118
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:18,000
No, I was stupid. I was glad. Sorry, I know I eat my words. That's funny. I got all these people helping me out. I'm thinking I'm being helped not realizing that a movement has started out there.

119
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:27,000
I wasn't too much into the national forefront of the political ends of this, but I was just amazed with Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling.

120
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:38,000
When I finally got to know who he was and Dr. (Martin Luther) King (Ralph) Abernathy, Hosea Williams and all these people started coming around. I was like a flower in a wall.

121
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:49,000
I mean, they probably never noticed me that I tried to sleep in the background, but yes, I would sit around and listen as best I could with what they had to say and what they were talking about.

122
00:26:49,000 --> 00:27:07,000
I was just a lady just to be out there to help. And yes, I particularly now recall after this, so right now it was passed around where we were kind of pressed to get people to go out to test the newly enacted.

123
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:17,000
The newly enacted law. And we did have people coming in from out of town a lot.

124
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:36,000
I went out myself on one demonstration, St. Augustine Beach. And with a group of four other teens and this white man.

125
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:43,000
He told me so tall white man. I think his name was Al Lengo. He told me so through the beach.

126
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:53,000
And we were in the surf maybe about 10, 15 minutes when you can see this large crowd of whites coming from north and south.

127
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:02,000
They were converging on our location. And we weren't too along because they were at a distance. They kept getting closer and closer.

128
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:08,000
So Mr. Lengo said, I guess we better get back in the car and leave.

129
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:18,000
It was a young teenage girl with us, a black girl. And she was running back to the car with his face as she could.

130
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:27,000
Now we were just casually running back. She got back to the car before us. And she locked all the doors.

131
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:32,000
And we could not get her to open. And we had enough time to get in the car and drive off. We kept pleading.

132
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:40,000
Open the door, open the door. And she was just hysterical crying. She was just frightened.

133
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:45,000
Just crying, boo, we kept pleading. Open the door, she wouldn't open the door.

134
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:51,000
So we had a crowd finding converged around the car. We were out.

135
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:56,000
So I don't want to. So I told her, so I'll get on one side of the car.

136
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:06,000
And they were taunting. They were threatening. They went to one truck and they pulled out angular weights.

137
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:12,000
Their intent was to bound them out of our hands and feed and take us as far out into the service.

138
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:21,000
And drop us. And I recall standing there thinking, well, Lord, I didn't think I'd go out this way.

139
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:31,000
Now, like I said, non-fellowns was a tactic. My life on the line, you coming out to me? I want to make sure that I leave a mark.

140
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:37,000
That was my thing. I was pretty much self-trained. What I thought was a little karate at the time.

141
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:43,000
So I swiped. Well, first guy that comes at me, I got to do what I got to do.

142
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:50,000
But I thought about it slowly one time. Well, maybe a run here or there might help.

143
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:55,000
I said, look, I have no white neighborhood. I would know it would run.

144
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:58,000
There's no place to run. I mean, he's all white for.

145
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:05,000
And at that time, my mindset was that most of the whites just hate black people.

146
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:14,000
I had a long life, but it just hate us. So I had very little trust for pretty much whites at that time,

147
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:22,000
sort of this man that we were with. And I'm just, well, maybe this is God's will.

148
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:26,000
So this is God's will. I have to accept it.

149
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:36,000
But one white kid walked past me and he punched me in the face.

150
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:45,000
I cut my lip over. I started to jump. I mean, you had a large mob. There were bats and chains.

151
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And the way to my own lingo put it saying across my chest and told me to stand my ground.

152
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:59,000
Don't fight back. Stand your ground. So it was hard as that was. I did.

153
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:04,000
And then he was hit. I recall over the head with a pipe.

154
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:11,000
The blood hit me in the face. And he collapsed pretty much unconscious next to me.

155
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:20,000
And at that time, now, you could hear at a distance, a police car sowing.

156
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:28,000
You could hear it. And seconds passed, the other sound grew louder and louder.

157
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:35,000
Until that a distance, I could see coming from the south, hit it in North, this police car.

158
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:40,000
This one loan police car. And as they got closer, the mob dispersed.

159
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:45,000
Because I think they felt they had killed this white guy out that they hit.

160
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:50,000
I think they, I thought the guy, I thought I heard his head crack open.

161
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:53,000
But they, they dispersed.

162
00:31:53,000 --> 00:32:01,000
Help was called. He was taking the hospital and we were taking back to Washington Street.

163
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:09,000
And I never get Hosea Williams was so angry. He said,

164
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:12,000
oh, they think they're going to scare us away from the beach.

165
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:21,000
We're going to come back stronger. So with that, a second demonstration was organized.

166
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:30,000
And a large group, it occurred about two weeks later, went back to St. Augustine Beach.

167
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:43,000
And I recalled getting off the bus, a cordon of helmeted police that we walked down between to the water.

168
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:53,000
And I think I forget the pastor's name that was leading the front of the march.

169
00:32:53,000 --> 00:33:00,000
But who I was in charge of, the group was at that time, came over to the group.

170
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:04,000
This time I made sure I was going to be in the front. That's what I got to go today.

171
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
I'm going to jail. I mean, I'm going to be in the front of this march.

172
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:13,000
Because I was still upset. I was hitting the face and, I mean, what have you.

173
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:22,000
But this police, when they, the group approached the front of the group,

174
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:28,000
and he told us, well, a little problem before you can get into the water,

175
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:34,000
we have to clear it of all these hostile lights in the water.

176
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:42,000
So give us a few minutes to clear it. But I assure you you will go into the ocean today.

177
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:43,000
The state trooper.

178
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:50,000
The state trooper. So we stood down on the edge of the surf.

179
00:33:50,000 --> 00:34:01,000
They went in just about waist deep. Florida state troopers, to force this angry mob out of the water.

180
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:08,000
I have never, to this day, seen a milley like it occurred that day.

181
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:17,000
The wipes in the water had two by fours, chains, bats, and the fight was on.

182
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:22,000
I mean, it lasted to me about 15, 20 minutes.

183
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:29,000
But the the Klan in their sympathizers were beaten into submission by white troopers.

184
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:37,000
I could not believe it. Now I'm really confused now because I'm saying, wow, I can't stand these white men beating up the other white men.

185
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:44,000
That's a new one for me. I was really shocked. But it was a milley.

186
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:54,000
They were knocking some of the the Klan, and their sympathizers out and dragging them up to the shoreline and dropping them and going back in for more.

187
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:00,000
When I say they were beaten into submission, believe me, I said, then watch it. I could not believe it.

188
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:07,000
And when it was over, the man in charge of these state troopers came back up to our group.

189
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:15,000
He said, look, okay, I think it's safe for you to go in now. I can't guarantee the quality of the water.

190
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:18,000
But it is safe for you to go in now.

191
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:20,000
He actually made that job.

192
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:27,000
He did. He said, rightfully so. Now, when I went through the edge, I looked at the water. I mean, it was bloody.

193
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:30,000
I mean, the blood was that thick in the water.

194
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:36,000
A few of the demonstrators did go around and go into the surf for a few minutes.

195
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:41,000
But it was so bloody. I was just going through it. I said, no, this water is too bloody.

196
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:49,000
And I mean, bloody. And I stood there thinking, I'm still kind of confused now.

197
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:58,000
I mean, these white men fight another white men for my civil rights. I'm trying to figure out for some of my seniors I had.

198
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:04,000
I'm confused. I had a shifting. I couldn't. I had to put that together. And it took a while.

199
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:12,000
But I do recall going on demonstrations, marches, or sit-ins, or now to test the law after that.

200
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:21,000
When these state troopers told the the Klan of their sympathizers to move, believe me, after that beating on the beach that day, they moved. That's one thing I do recall.

201
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:25,000
How did you ultimately explain it? Why did that happen?

202
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:32,000
The troop was coming down. And taking that action.

203
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:36,000
I guess it was. I think they were ordered down here from Farris Bryant.

204
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:40,000
Governor just decided we're just going to not keep having this happen.

205
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:41,000
Right.

206
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:43,000
We just find work and move on.

207
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:46,000
Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling is mentioning also the (US) Justice Department.

208
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:51,000
There were these wider forces coming down to stop the early pattern of violence.

209
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:54,000
There's always a lot of people involved.

210
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:57,000
There's kind of, I think, I don't need to cut you out there.

211
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:01,000
Maybe more to say on that. But I also, I would be very appreciative of it.

212
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:17,000
You could sort of double back and contextualize that moment by talking for a minute or two about the previous pattern of local law enforcement engagement with the Klan and in the context of these demonstrations.

213
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:25,000
Well, my vantage point, I, oh, I could, what I realized was that the police were not sympathetic to the demonstrated.

214
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:27,000
And just the opposite.

215
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:35,000
And again, having been involved with a couple of situations involving the police.

216
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:42,000
No, my biggest fear was if I was ever arrested, I'd probably be beaten by the local police.

217
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:45,000
But fortunately, I was never arrested.

218
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:56,000
I had a situation where, again, being involved at a tutorial school on Washington Street.

219
00:37:56,000 --> 00:38:01,000
The young lady had a class of youth.

220
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:05,000
I think the oldest body being a six or seven.

221
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:13,000
She decided to take a small group to the movie theater here downtown.

222
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:17,000
I didn't think of it wise. It's like I said, this is not the passage of civil rights act.

223
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:20,000
And I cautioned, I said, look, I don't think it's a good idea.

224
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:24,000
Oh, we'll be okay. She was by herself.

225
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:34,000
But anyhow, I decided to hang around in front of the church of the edge of Washington Street there for a couple hours until the safety return from the moon.

226
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:40,000
Within 20 minutes, I could hear a kid scream.

227
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:50,000
So I walked again, you know, over to the one block over where the St. Augustine record is located, considered to be a white area at that time.

228
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:53,000
If you made it back to Washington Street, you were safe. That was a black area.

229
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:59,000
And I could see the kids running towards me screaming, hysterically.

230
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:10,000
And this young white female who had taken them to the movie, she's got one kid in a hand and she's trying to write.

231
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:17,000
And I see this white male on a bicycle with a knife chasing them.

232
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:22,000
Now, I intervened and stopped.

233
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:29,000
Unfortunately, I was surrounded by two hulking policemen.

234
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:33,000
And I felt, well, they're probably going to beat me up.

235
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:37,000
But they had a police dog.

236
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:39,000
So I guess they get me.

237
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:43,000
But I could see the crowd on Washington Street gathered and looking over.

238
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:49,000
And a couple of friends of mine came up to the policemen and said, well, what are you doing?

239
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:52,000
You told them you little niggas get away from there.

240
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:55,000
No, that's our friend. What are you doing?

241
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:57,000
Then we take to get away from it.

242
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:00,000
So one of the young men pushed the policemen and took off running.

243
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:03,000
So the policemen were so upset at that.

244
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:07,000
They started chasing my two friends and left me there.

245
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:11,000
But before one of the cops left, he told his dog, if he moves, kill him.

246
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:13,000
So the dog sat and started growling.

247
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:15,000
I said, oh, wow.

248
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:21,000
The German Shepherd and the policeman could not catch my two friends.

249
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:24,000
So I could see them headed back toward me.

250
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:26,000
And I'm looking at the dog. He's growling.

251
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:28,000
I'm looking at the policeman approaching me.

252
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:32,000
The dog's growling. That's what I had to make a decision.

253
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:39,000
So I said, well, what I'm going to do is I'm facing the dog and Washington Street is at my back.

254
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:46,000
I must turn slowly and run as hard as I can back to Washington Street.

255
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:50,000
This is only a good block to run.

256
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:52,000
The Ford or the policeman get it.

257
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:57,000
And so I slowly turn the dog as well in the whole time.

258
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:00,000
And I took off as fast as I could.

259
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:04,000
As hard as I could run back to Washington Street.

260
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:07,000
When I get there, people are waiting. They were clapping.

261
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:10,000
So I tried to run a look. The dog didn't even move.

262
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:14,000
He was still sitting there.

263
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:19,000
So now I'm talking to police. Yeah, come over here now. Come get me. Come get me.

264
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:24,000
Anyhow, some of the folks are, look, you better go ahead and go home, which I did.

265
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:29,000
Now I hit out for a while.

266
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:33,000
Two days actually in one of the church shards.

267
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:36,000
And people from the community would come by and give me water and sandwiches.

268
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:39,000
You hit out in the church yard because you thought the police were going to find you.

269
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:41,000
Yes. And take it. Yeah.

270
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:46,000
You hit out in the church yard. Yeah. Two days.

271
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:50,000
Two days, two nights. They would bring the water and sandwiches.

272
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:56,000
They don't worry about anything. Your parents, we throw your parents everything is safe. We'll take care of you.

273
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:00,000
When it happened inside the movie theater, it drives better.

274
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:02,000
I never found out.

275
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:07,000
But I like I say, we're only talking months after the passage.

276
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:18,000
So a lot of people were felt everything was okay and no need now to continue to demonstrate or to test the law.

277
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:25,000
You mentioned there was a white student, young adult, I guess, doing this tutoring of young black children.

278
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:27,000
And she had taken them into this movie theater.

279
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:28,000
Yes.

280
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:32,000
Obviously there were some whites from Northern colleges.

281
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:38,000
Other contexts came down and had different roles in some way in their way.

282
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:43,000
Did you did that involvement of whites?

283
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:47,000
You mentioned Mr. Langel earlier in the beach incident.

284
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:52,000
How do you take the measure of these white folks who would get involved?

285
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:57,000
Well, believe it or not, those college kids, white, and they were pretty good group.

286
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:03,000
Those white college kids changed my perspective of whites.

287
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:08,000
I thought all whites hated me and other blacks just because we were black.

288
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:10,000
But they changed my perspective.

289
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:18,000
You had one particular college student, Gail Blattenberg.

290
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:27,000
I recently contacted her about two months ago.

291
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:29,000
And through emails.

292
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:31,000
But she was like a mother in the end of it.

293
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:35,000
She was only a few years older.

294
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:39,000
But surprisingly, she's a story.

295
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:45,000
You had a group of kids from certain states in the North.

296
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:48,000
She was from Princeton, New Jersey at the time.

297
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:51,000
You had some other kids from Massachusetts, all of it.

298
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:56,000
So what they did when their tutorial session was over here in St. Augustine,

299
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:03,000
they invited a group of black kids who participated in the program back to their homes.

300
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:07,000
And my mother didn't want me to go.

301
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:09,000
She's too young.

302
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:11,000
I'm sorry.

303
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:13,000
I can't let him go.

304
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:16,000
I was a little bit greedy with my mother, my employees.

305
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:17,000
I like to go.

306
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:19,000
It was a two-week trip.

307
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:21,000
She wouldn't.

308
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:22,000
She's a no.

309
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:24,000
I'm worried about you.

310
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:26,000
I don't know too much about the North.

311
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:30,000
And I don't want you to go up there by yourself with these kids.

312
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:33,000
And they were young students themselves.

313
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:38,000
But anyhow, surprisingly, they made up picket signs and picket.

314
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:43,000
They were like, hey, I'm going to go to the house to try to get my mother to relent

315
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:47,000
and let me go for that two-week trip with them.

316
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:48,000
Everybody was a laugh.

317
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:51,000
This is one of these kids on a picket in the car.

318
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:54,000
But my mother would come home every day and see where the laugh.

319
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:55,000
She thought it was very funny.

320
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:59,000
So finally, she would let it in and allow me to go on that two-week trip.

321
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:03,000
But I stayed with the Gil Blatt and Berg and her parents.

322
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:05,000
And what a trip it was.

323
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:07,000
It's a very good trip.

324
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:10,000
It changed my whole perspective of white folk.

325
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:15,000
Because the only white folk I knew was the ones here in St. Augustine, pretty much.

326
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:19,000
And again, like I see, not that they were nasty,

327
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:23,000
it's just the way the treatment like you were subhuman or something.

328
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:26,000
I mean, no respect.

329
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:28,000
That's what I had.

330
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:33,000
But those college kids coming on, you had a totally different perspective.

331
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:40,000
Taking you through late 64 or 65, 66 and how you found your way through that period,

332
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:45,000
your perspective on St. Augustine is it's reacting to the Civil Rights Act's passage

333
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:50,000
to the Voting Rights Act of 1965 the next year to...

334
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:54,000
It took a while for...

335
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:02,000
I mean, we may be talking a year to kind of get into the...

336
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:05,000
The mindset of the business community here, the white business community.

337
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:09,000
But yes, all right, this is the law and you have to adhere to it.

338
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:11,000
Now, I never had a problem.

339
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Now, I came to the same movie theater myself.

340
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:20,000
I never forget to watch one of the James Bond movies with no problem.

341
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Restaurants know my money pocket wasn't that tight.

342
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:26,000
It started hitting the restaurants.

343
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:28,000
But, you know, I didn't have a problem.

344
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:42,000
More at ease now coming to the downtown white area that I had been used probably.

345
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:45,000
As you move through that early...

346
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:54,000
That those close months, that close year or two after the heaviest of the...

347
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:58,000
All these moments charged with so much potential violence, actual violence.

348
00:46:58,000 --> 00:47:00,000
Did you...

349
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:02,000
How did you deal with all that?

350
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:04,000
And it's sort of the way I carried forward with you.

351
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:08,000
Was that something that you were able to step forward and away from without too much difficulty?

352
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:11,000
Did you feel it or did you...?

353
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:13,000
Not much.

354
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:15,000
See, I was...

355
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:18,000
I didn't think what I...

356
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:23,000
Most of my friends or fellow demonstrators were doing was of any significance.

357
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:26,000
I just felt like, hey, this is something that had to be done.

358
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:29,000
So I didn't place that much importance on it.

359
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:30,000
But I knew...

360
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:35,000
I was just happy that we accomplished some things.

361
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:42,000
I wasn't even aware when I was demonstrating too much about a civil rights act or a Voting Rights Act of 1965.

362
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:47,000
But I was just happy that these things had occurred.

363
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Now, it would help me.

364
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:59,000
Now, I want to go into a junior college in Daytona Beach where I met my wife who was going to Bethune-Cookman.

365
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:03,000
It was a trade school.

366
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:09,000
Now, I took up a brick masonry.

367
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:13,000
We had a black instructor.

368
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:16,000
The class pretty much was predominantly black.

369
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:23,000
It was the first two-year course for the first year and a half.

370
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:34,000
We were scheduled to go in and take our final exam with, I think, some city agency in Daytona Beach.

371
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:40,000
Now, in the year and a half, we were there, the black students.

372
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:48,000
The last six months, you had these two white students that come into the course.

373
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:59,000
And within a few months, they were allowed to go take the test and become a mason.

374
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:01,000
And my teacher was outraged.

375
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:02,000
He said, wait a minute.

376
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:03,000
What do you...

377
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:04,000
What do you...

378
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:05,000
What do you...

379
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:08,000
What do you mean that the only people...

380
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:11,000
These guys are not even trained. They're only been here a few months.

381
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,000
I got these young black men I've trained for the last year and a half.

382
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:21,000
And you mean to tell me, you're not going to allow them to go and take the test of finals so they can get their permits and what have you?

383
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:25,000
School of the Ministry of Reviews.

384
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:31,000
My instructor, through pro-testing, was fired.

385
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:37,000
We were called to the Ministry of Office and offered a settlement

386
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:45,000
because we had a year and a half under this course that if we wanted our certificates, two years certificate,

387
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:52,000
that we'd have to spend the last six months in a carpentry class.

388
00:49:52,000 --> 00:50:01,000
And believe it or not, two white guys even though only had three months of training, they were given their certificates at work in the construction.

389
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:03,000
We all refused.

390
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:12,000
So I never received, even though I did a year and a half, a day to a beach community college in their program.

391
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:14,000
I'd never received anything for it.

392
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:17,000
We weren't even reimbursed.

393
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:18,000
So that was the end of that.

394
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:27,000
But fortunately, I married and my wife was from New York.

395
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:35,000
We moved back with herf parents in New York and I got employment there.

396
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:44,000
But racism, I found, was not just a southern issue.

397
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:47,000
It was worse in the north.

398
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:52,000
At least in the south, it was overt in the north that's a pet on the back and a smile on the face.

399
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:55,000
In a stab you, as often as I can.

400
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:01,000
I worked in post office my first five years.

401
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:05,000
Again, here I am doing a counting for a supervisor.

402
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:08,000
Who can even do it?

403
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:14,000
But he's being paid more money just to be over the blacks.

404
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:17,000
Excuse me.

405
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:24,000
Fortunately, the Civil Rights Act was important in its passage because it did open the floodbed.

406
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:29,000
I would put it that way for black opportunities, particularly in the north.

407
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:38,000
Most of the people I went in with in the post over the time were pretty much because of the Civil Rights Act.

408
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:45,000
But I always looked for advancement and opportunities that there was very little in the post office.

409
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:53,000
I tried to petition for the take exams to know a veil.

410
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:59,000
But after five years I passed police department's test and went into that.

411
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:01,000
Were you in New York City?

412
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:05,000
Yes.

413
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:08,000
Now there, the racism was just as rampant.

414
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:19,000
And I would say more intimidating because it's more of a rank and file organization as you know, police.

415
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:24,000
You got your sergeant, Lieutenant, Captain, on up.

416
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:34,000
But somebody high-awky that I worked under felt like I was still some type of nigger that they could talk to anyway wanted.

417
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:43,000
Again, like I said, that's what my training, my involvement in Civil Rights here in the Civil Rights Act prepared me for that.

418
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:49,000
It's like I didn't allow the disrespect regardless of who you were when I was a teen.

419
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:52,000
I didn't allow it working in the police department.

420
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:56,000
So my attitude was you curse me out no matter what your rank.

421
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:01,000
I would likewise in turn speak as you speak to me.

422
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:05,000
You know, I respect your rank as long as you respect me as a human being.

423
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:11,000
And I did run into some, a lot of, with that attitude, you had, oh boy,

424
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:14,000
some of the worst of the worst out to you.

425
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:21,000
But another thing was for sure, from me, most of the guys, particularly blacks that I entered the police department,

426
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:25,000
when it came out of the Civil Rights Movement, surprisingly.

427
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:33,000
And we were cohesive and they were as demanding for respect as I was.

428
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:35,000
Some more so.

429
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:37,000
So that made it a lot easier.

430
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:43,000
I was proud to see a lot of the folk and the females, black females were the ones.

431
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:46,000
I mean, they did not take any shit.

432
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:50,000
So let's see if I can put it that way from there.

433
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:56,000
So curious because I think that getting these jobs, I can see that the racism involved,

434
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:02,000
what's the try to still keep you as low as possible.

435
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:12,000
And it didn't work because a group, I got together with a group, the Suits, the police department,

436
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:16,000
and the city of New York for discriminating on the promotional exams.

437
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:19,000
And we were successful.

438
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:28,000
I again had the suit with the same similar suit for my lieutenants exam, and we were successful.

439
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:34,000
And those lawsuits were used, the criteria was used around the nation.

440
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:37,000
And they were still being used at this day.

441
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:43,000
So yes, the Civil Rights Movement in Augustine prepared me well.

442
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:49,000
Did the department change gradually in your service there over time?

443
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:54,000
Did you think it changed because of this ongoing pattern of challenge and activism?

444
00:54:54,000 --> 00:55:01,000
Definitely. I think the change came about not so much willingly.

445
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:09,000
The first lawsuit, I guess the New York City Police Department, when it came to the sergeants test,

446
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:13,000
produced, and this is what changed the complexion of the job.

447
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:18,000
It produced over 300 minority candidates.

448
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:22,000
Now they called us quota sergeants at the time.

449
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:31,000
And the theory was that we couldn't perform, we were given a break, and it was just the contrary.

450
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:35,000
Now I left my position as a lieutenant with honors.

451
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:43,000
I trained most of the people that worked under me, particularly white candidates.

452
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:45,000
And well, to this day I respected.

453
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:57,000
And my whole focus to them was you treat, you see a woman out there, black, white, green, or blue, you treat her like your mother.

454
00:55:57,000 --> 00:56:07,000
You know, I don't expect you to bring this white mentality into a black neighborhood on how to treat people.

455
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:16,000
And if I ever see or hear of any of the guys I train treating someone harshly, you have to deal with me.

456
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:23,000
Don't worry about someone looking you up under your apartment doing an investigation, because I'll be the first to drop a dime on you.

457
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:26,000
I'll be the first to put you on a foot.

458
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:35,000
So honestly, honestly, I never, I trained hundreds.

459
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:46,000
I never had a serious complaint of any white male or female officer under my supervision, never in my career.

460
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,000
Did you come back to say, obviously, in those years?

461
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:50,000
Yes, I would come every year.

462
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:53,000
And my parents were still here, my brothers, my family was still here.

463
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:59,000
So I'd bring my kids down every summer just to give me a wife of break.

464
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:02,000
And they loved it.

465
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:10,000
And surprisingly, I know you're talking about the YMCA when they would come down.

466
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:14,000
My mother would put them in this women program at the YMCA.

467
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:17,000
Let's take a break for just one second.

468
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:19,000
Okay, we're back after short break.

469
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:27,000
I just, I was asking about your return business in Augustine over the years, family here, and much kids down and all.

470
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:31,000
How did your opinion of the city and racialism to the city evolve over time?

471
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:34,000
How can you sort of track that for me?

472
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:40,000
Well, not living here in St. Augustine.

473
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:53,000
I can't give an opinion, but what I'm really disheartened at the non-improvement of black life here in St. Augustine.

474
00:57:53,000 --> 00:58:09,000
I would come back to see abandoned houses, drug ravaged areas, particularly black seniors not receiving assistance.

475
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:14,000
To keep their properties up.

476
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:22,000
I started seeing what I had witnessed in certain areas in New York at one time, due to red-lining.

477
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:26,000
And I felt like this is what was happening in St. Augustine.

478
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:31,000
Blacks couldn't get the loans for their properties.

479
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:35,000
I knew how the system of red-lining was worked.

480
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:39,000
It starts with the banks not lending money.

481
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:54,000
It starts with the Kee of the neighborhood, coupled with the raising of taxes, and then the gentrification.

482
00:58:54,000 --> 00:59:02,000
And this is what has played out in Lincolnville over the last ten years.

483
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:08,000
What's your sense of the...

484
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:23,000
You mentioned that very central point about how you experience this here in the movement probably substantially were reflected in the way you approach the challenge of the racial challenges structurally in police work.

485
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:37,000
And even prior to the community college and the choices you made about how to respond to the injustice of the firing of your instructor and the easy passage of these two white students into credential.

486
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:46,000
I'm interested in your sense of other ways in which the experience here has been reflected in your life as you've gone forward.

487
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:54,000
And perhaps as a parent, perhaps as a person who contributes to your community and through professional service in other ways?

488
00:59:54,000 --> 01:00:02,000
Well, this, like some of my experiences growing up here, I was raised by my agreeable grandmother.

489
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:07,000
I'm not valent, but I'm not passive either.

490
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:12,000
If I'm put in a position where I have to respond physically, I will.

491
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:25,000
Fortunately, I was not put in that position in the police department, but I think my determination in will is what was a force that I think protected me pretty much.

492
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:30,000
I think those around me knew that I would respond.

493
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:47,000
What I learned as a second level of level manager in the police department is this buddy system, you know, viewed by me as races.

494
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:59,000
Now, I'm going to stand you taking care of your buddy or your friend, which is not a bad thing, but as a whole.

495
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:07,000
I mean, when you have, let's say, whites that are in authority that make decisions as crucial to the group.

496
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:13,000
If everything is going to be based on a buddy system, I started seeing this and I would challenge that with a lot of my white friends.

497
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:15,000
I say, it's not fair.

498
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:23,000
You know, when you get someone who is qualified to do the job, you need to put that person first.

499
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:33,000
I mean, if there's a slot open for a buddy, then you, you know, but I started seeing this mentality of this buddy system pretty much more in place.

500
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:37,000
And I thought that my white colleagues didn't do that as being races.

501
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:44,000
And I say, it is because who is your buddy is the guy that you live around, the guy that you drink with?

502
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:46,000
You're not drinking with me.

503
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:49,000
You're not drinking with the guys like me.

504
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:56,000
So that's why you find yourself not putting them on the same scale as your buddy.

505
01:01:56,000 --> 01:01:59,000
So your buddy is always going to make out.

506
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:04,000
And I think this is the whole, my own personal mind.

507
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:07,000
So is this the whole makeup of this whole system we live in?

508
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:09,000
Everything is a buddy system.

509
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:11,000
It's who you know. It's not what you know.

510
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:13,000
And that's the way I see it now.

511
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:15,000
You've moved back to Florida?

512
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:17,000
Yes.

513
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:19,000
Yeah, I'm in Palm Coast, FL now.

514
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:23,000
Did you, did you, would you guess that you would have done that when you moved away?

515
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:25,000
Yes. You always thought we'd be fine.

516
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:27,000
I know, I know we were going to come back.

517
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:29,000
I think we knew we were going to come back.

518
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:31,000
I mean, who can beat this weather?

519
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:41,000
If you were a makeup, you would imagine making a walk through the neighborhood here.

520
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:44,000
And a walk through Lincolnville.

521
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:50,000
And imagine pausing it a few places because key memories that you haven't shared previously really came out.

522
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:54,000
What, can you imagine what a few of those stories might be?

523
01:02:54,000 --> 01:03:02,000
My passion now, and this is before the city, is the little links to Gatwood also security Gellimore Center.

524
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:10,000
That pool has, which I understand was managed by the county for the last few years, has been closed for over two years.

525
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:20,000
Now, I petition the city commissioners with some historical facts from 15 years ago.

526
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:23,000
And I hope they listen.

527
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:27,000
See, the little links was more than just a park.

528
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:31,000
It actually was a sanctuary for me, and I'm quite sure a lot of people.

529
01:03:31,000 --> 01:03:33,000
And I think it still is.

530
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:44,000
I don't know what the cities and tenants in that area, but I hope it is to restore it to its glory and repair and put that pool open for all of you.

531
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:45,000
I hope it is that way.

532
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:46,000
I don't know.

533
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:51,000
All I can do is just continue to fight for that.

534
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:53,000
But that's one area.

535
01:03:53,000 --> 01:03:57,000
I had so many, many great days.

536
01:03:57,000 --> 01:04:03,000
And I'm quite sure you have quite a few young kids at the time, probably in my age, now they can say that.

537
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:13,000
That was the only sanctuary you could go to to get away from all this hatred and bigotry and discrimination.

538
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:14,000
That was it.

539
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:18,000
You went there, fun, fun, fun all day.

540
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:20,000
So that's one spot.

541
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:23,000
I think it actually, in my heart, the only spot.

542
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:25,000
And just...

543
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:33,000
Can you put up some meeting and if we can meet after the...

544
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:36,000
Yeah, Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling has just said that...

545
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:41,000
Just Conway is leading an ongoing effort to try to reactivate that whole...

546
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:44,000
The center, we got more center in...

547
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:51,000
I know that there is much, much more we could talk about.

548
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:55,000
And you're such a great narrator that you've taken me through a nice arc here.

549
01:04:55,000 --> 01:05:04,000
Are the other things you want to come back to touch upon before we finish other scenes, other moments, other thoughts?

550
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:07,000
Well, I think...

551
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:17,000
In a lot of communities, you have a lot of black activism, particularly political.

552
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:23,000
St. Augustine now is just at that stage of getting there.

553
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:34,000
I was asked a question, a panel once, why blacks are not involved in city affairs and civic affairs?

554
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:37,000
And I'll respond the same way.

555
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:45,000
You cannot keep a race of people out of political spectrum for decades

556
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:52,000
and expect when you pass an act, a civil rights bill or any other bill, that all of a sudden there's both a flood of gates

557
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:55,000
and come back in the civic duty.

558
01:05:55,000 --> 01:06:06,000
And I think again, I was not raised into political spectrum, but be a civic minded, just like I'm quite sure, generations,

559
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:11,000
particularly here in Lincolnville and West Augustine behind me weren't raised.

560
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:21,000
I think if you know, once those folks understand the importance of it,

561
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:27,000
you're slot-seeing them returning and being more active with their civic duties.

562
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:32,000
And that's what I, another thing I've been trying to explain and push.

563
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:34,000
Successfully, too. I've seen it.

564
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:37,000
There is a lot more activism than it was a year or two ago.

565
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:40,000
I see that. I'm really proud of it.

566
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:43,000
I really want to thank you. It's been a real honor and privilege.

567
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:49,000
And I, at least thank you again also for the extra flexibility in our day schedule, but it's been great to be with you.

568
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:50,000
Thank you.

569
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:51,000
Thank you.

570
01:06:51,000 --> 01:07:02,000
Before we close, it leads to a tribute to Mother Anne and her daughter.

571
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:09,000
Yeah, I mean, it was to sure I believe you, so for sure, grandly.

572
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:11,000
Yeah, let me do that. Are we still 100?

573
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:12,000
Okay.

574
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:16,000
Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling is suggesting George Conway.

575
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:23,000
Yeah, Dr. (Robert B.) Hayling suggested that Ms. Conway call out his parents and let me have you name them and talk a little about them before we close.

576
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:25,000
That's lovely. Thank you.

577
